The paper deals with improving the training of convolutional neural networks, which is a common topic in computer vision (cs.CV) and machine learning (cs.LG). The paper also introduces a new ranking criteria for selecting filters to prune, which falls under the category of artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The use of modern network architectures such as skip/dense connections and Inception units suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the field of neural networks (cs.NE). Finally, the paper's focus on improving generalization suggests that it may also be relevant to natural language processing (cs.CL), where generalization is an important problem.
